  <section id="about">
    <h2>About Me</h2>
    <p>
      Hi! My name is Dalton Craven. I'm a software engineer and recent graduate
      of the University of South Carolina. I'm a big proponent of web
      accessibility and localization techniques to ensure that the web stays
      open for all.
    </p>

    <section id="journey">
      <h3>My Journey</h3>
      <p>
        I've always been fascinated by technology and the way it can be used to
        solve problems. I was first introduced to the world of computer science
        in high school through <a href="https://hackclub.com">Hack Club</a>, a
        network of student-run programming organizations. I then went on to
        study both theoretical and applied computer science at the University of
        South Carolina, where I graduated summa cum laude with a B.S.C.S. in
        Computer Science.
      </p>
      <p>
        During my time at USC, I had the opportunity to study abroad in Paris
        and intern at <a href="https://qantev.com">Qantev</a>, a French tech
        start-up. These experiences were invaluable in shaping my worldview and
        broadening my horizons. I was able to experience a new culture, learn a
        new language, and make lifelong friends. I also gained a deeper
        appreciation for the importance of localization and accessibility in
        software development.
      </p>
      <p>
        I'm currently back in Paris working as a full-stack software engineer at
        Qantev, where I'm helping to build a platform that will revolutionize
        the way insurance companies manage their data. I'm also working on a few
        personal projects, including a website for my photography hobby and a
        toolkit for ballroom dance.
      </p>
    </section>
