  <section id="projects">
    <h2>Projects</h2>
    <div>
      <h3>Wordification: A New Way of Teaching English Spelling Patterns</h3>

      <p>
        Wordification is a set of online games designed to teach spelling
        through the linkage of phonemes and graphemes, encouraging students to
        learn spelling rules phonetically rather than memorizing static spelling
        lists. Wordification is currently in the proof-of-concept stage, but our
        team is eagerly looking forward to conducting real-world, peer-reviewed
        trials with students soon. We recently submitted a research paper to a
        paper about Wordification to the <a
          href="https://www.american-cse.org/csce2023/conferences-FECS"
          >19<sup>th</sup> International Conference on Frontiers in Education: Computer
          Science & Computer Engineering</a
        >, which was accepted for publication — we're excited about presenting
        our work ths July. Wordification is built with Redwood and Typescript,
        and is <a href="https://github.com/wordification/app"
          >visible on GitHub</a
        >.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3>DKMS: Social Media Features for Spotify</h3>

      <p>
        For my senior capstone project, I led a team of five in designing and
        implementing a unique application — one that enriches the Spotify
        experience by integrating social media features. Given the significant
        workload, I assumed multiple roles — developer, devops manager, and
        scrum master. The final product was a full-stack web application built
        with Next.js, Typescript, Firestore, and the Spotify Web SDK. Some key
        features included the ability to dynamically load content, tailored
        recommendations based on a user's listening activity, and audio analysis
        of songs, albums, artists, and playlists. The project is <a
          href="https://dkms.vercel.app">deployed on Vercel</a
        >, and the code is
        <a href="https://github.com/sccapstone/dkms">visible on GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
